    statementOfFactsText: `At the time when Islam appeared, Arabia had two kinds of rulers.
None of the crowned kings held complete independence.
Tribal and clan chiefs possessed authority similar to that of kings within their regions.
Tribal and clan chiefs were largely independent, except for those who showed limited submission to an external monarch.
Crowned kings were found only in Yemen, al-Hirah, and Ghassan.
All other rulers in Arabia were tribal leaders without crowns.
Before 650 B.C., the rulers of Sheba carried the title “Mukarrib of Sheba.”
The capital of Sheba during this era was Sarwah, also called Khriba, located west of Marib.
During this period, construction of the Marib Dam began.
Between 650 B.C. and 115 B.C., the rulers abandoned the title “Mukarrib” and adopted the title “Kings of Sheba.”
Between 650 B.C. and 115 B.C., the capital shifted from Sarwah to Marib.
Between 115 B.C. and 300 A.D., the Himyar tribe gained dominance over Sheba.
The capital moved to Raydan, later called Zafar, near present-day Yarim.
The Romans conquered Egypt, Syria, and northern Arabia.
Many of the Qahtani tribes dispersed into various regions of Arabia.
Roman forces briefly controlled Aden.
Roman forces used Aden as a strategic base.
The Abyssinians invaded Yemen around 340 A.D., holding it for several decades.
Yemen later regained independence after the Abyssinians’ withdrawal.
A major collapse of the Marib Dam occurred during this time.
The collapse of the Marib Dam caused the dispersal of the settled peoples of Yemen.
In 523 A.D., Dhu Nawas, a Himyarite ruler who had adopted Judaism, launched a campaign against the Christians of Najran.
He attempted to force them to convert.
He killed a number of them by burning a large trench filled with fire.
“Cursed were the people of the ditch.” (Quran 85:4)
In 525 A.D., the Abyssinians sent a large military force to Yemen.
Their commander Aryat became ruler.
Aryat was killed by Abraha, one of his own military leaders.
After reconciling with the Abyssinian king, Abraha assumed control of Yemen.
Abraha later marched toward Makkah intending to destroy the Ka’bah.
Islamic sources refer to this event as the incident of the Elephant.
The incident of the Elephant is mentioned in Surah al-Fil.
After the Elephant incident, the people of Yemen rose up under Madikarib ibn Saif Dhu Yazin al-Himyari.
Madikarib ibn Saif Dhu Yazin al-Himyari sought assistance from Persia.
With Persian military help, the Abyssinians were defeated.
Independence was restored in Yemen.
Madikarib ruled briefly.
Madikarib was assassinated by an Abyssinian servant.
After his death, the Persian ruler Kisra appointed a Persian governor over Yemen.
Yemen became a Persian province.
Persian rule continued until the time of Islam.
The last Persian governor, Badhan, accepted Islam after receiving the letter of the Prophet Muhammad.
With Badhan’s conversion, Persian rule in Yemen ended.`,
