    statementOfFactsText: `At the beginning of the fourth year of the Call, the idolaters of Quraysh intensified their hostility.
The chiefs of Makkah consulted one another and agreed on a more severe campaign to halt the spread of Islam.
They resolved to malign the Messenger of Allah and to inflict harm and torture upon his followers, especially those who had no powerful clan to protect them.
It was easier for them to carry out their plans against the weak and those without family support.
Protection from his uncle Abū Ṭālib made open assault on the Messenger of Allah more difficult.
Abū Lahab, the Prophet’s paternal uncle, was among the foremost in hostility.
Abū Lahab incited his sons to divorce Ruqayyah and Umm Kulthūm, the Prophet’s daughters.
Abū Lahab gloated when the Prophet’s sons died in childhood and referred to him as “cut off” with no male offspring.
Abū Lahab followed the Prophet during seasons and gatherings, warning tribes against him and belittling his call.
His wife, Umm Jamīl bint Ḥarb, placed thorns and harmful materials in pathways the Prophet might take.
Umm Jamīl bint Ḥarb spread slander and incitement against the Prophet.
Some neighbors of the Prophet threw filth and impurities in his path or near his dwelling.
While the Messenger of Allah was prostrating near the Ka‘bah, some leaders of Quraysh were sitting together.
One of them suggested bringing the entrails of a slaughtered she-camel and placing them on his back while he was in prostration.
‘Uqbah ibn Abī Mu‘ayṭ brought the filth and placed it on the Prophet’s back while he was in sujūd.
Those present laughed among themselves until some of them leaned over one another from amusement.
Fāṭimah, the Prophet’s daughter, came and removed the filth from his back and rebuked them.
After completing his prayer, the Prophet supplicated against certain named individuals present.
It was recorded that those named were later killed at Badr.
Among those who frequently attacked the Prophet with slander and insult were Umayyah ibn Khalaf and ‘Uqbah ibn Abī Mu‘ayṭ.
‘Uqbah once sat in a gathering of the Prophet and listened to him.
Ubayy ibn Khalaf reproached ‘Uqbah and demanded that he show enmity to the Prophet.
‘Uqbah then went to the Prophet and behaved with great disrespect.
Ubayy ibn Khalaf took old decomposed bones, crushed them, and blew the dust toward the Prophet.
Abū Jahl tried to prevent the Prophet from praying at the Ka‘bah.
Abū Jahl threatened to step on the Prophet’s neck while he was in prostration.
When Abū Jahl advanced intending to do so, he turned back, retreating and shielding himself with his hands.
Whenever Abū Jahl heard that a man of standing from Quraysh had embraced Islam, he questioned his judgment and threatened his trade and social position.
If the new Muslim was weak in clan support, Abū Jahl resorted to physical abuse and harsh punishments.
‘Uthmān ibn ‘Affān was confined and pressured by a relative from Banī Umayyah because of his Islam.
Mus‘ab ibn ‘Umayr’s mother and family turned against him.
Mus‘ab ibn ‘Umayr’s mother deprived him of her support and cut off his means.
Bilāl ibn Rabāḥ was the slave of Umayyah ibn Khalaf.
Umayyah and his associates took Bilāl out in the blazing heat of Makkah, laid him on the burning sand, and placed heavy stones on his chest.
They starved and thirsted Bilāl and tied a rope around his neck so that street boys could drag him.
Abū Bakr purchased Bilāl from Umayyah and set him free.
Abū Bakr bought and freed other oppressed believers who had no protectors.
‘Ammār ibn Yāsir and his parents, Yāsir and Sumayyah, were clients of Banī Makhzūm.
The family of Yāsir were taken out to the desert, exposed to the blazing sun, and tortured repeatedly.
The Messenger of Allah passed by the family of Yāsir while they were being punished.
Yāsir died under torture.
Sumayyah was killed by a spear thrust.
Under extreme pressure, ‘Ammār uttered some words outwardly displeasing to his tormentors.
‘Ammār came to the Messenger of Allah greatly distressed.
Abū Fakīhah, a freedman of Banī ‘Abd al-Dār, was tied by his feet and dragged through the streets of Makkah.
Khabbāb ibn al-Aratt, a blacksmith, was laid on burning coals so that the fat from his back extinguished them.
Khabbāb was pressed down with heavy weights so that he could not escape.
Some believing men of rank were wrapped in coarse skins, confined, or made to wear iron armor and left under the searing sun.
Some believers were beaten and humiliated in public.
Believing women including Zunayrah, al-Nahdiyyah and her daughter, and Umm ‘Ubays were beaten and oppressed.
Before he accepted Islam, ‘Umar ibn al-Khaṭṭāb punished some believing women.
Abū Bakr used his wealth to purchase and free oppressed believing women.`,
