    statementOfFactsText: `In the early period, some of the believers would go to the outskirts and hillocks of Makkah to meet with the Prophet.
Reports in the early Sīrah mention that in the fourth year of Prophethood a group of Muslims were heading out to a secluded place when some of the polytheists attacked them.
Sa‘d ibn Abī Waqqāṣ struck one of them, wounding him.
These reports describe this as the first bloodshed that occurred between Muslims and idolaters in Makkah.
In what is commonly placed in the fifth year of his mission, he took the house of al-Arqam ibn Abī al-Arqam at the foot of Mount al-Ṣafā as a private meeting place.
The house of al-Arqam was in Makkah.
Persecution of the Muslims began in the later part of the fourth year of Prophethood.
Abyssinia was a land to the west across the sea where there reigned a Christian king known as al-Najāshī (the Negus).
In the month of Rajab of the fifth year of Prophethood, a first small group of Muslims left Makkah for Abyssinia.
Early Sīrah accounts mention that they were twelve men and four women.
Among them were ‘Uthmān ibn ‘Affān and his wife Ruqayyah, the daughter of the Messenger of Allah.
They traveled until they reached the coast, where they found ships ready to sail to Abyssinia.
They boarded and departed safely.
Quraysh sent some men in pursuit after learning of their departure.
By the time the pursuers reached the shore, the Muslims had already crossed the sea.
The emigrants arrived in Abyssinia under the protection of al-Najāshī.
In this period, among the Makkan revelations was Sūrat al-Kahf (Chapter 18).
In Ramaḍān of the same year, the Messenger of Allah entered the Sacred Mosque while many of the notables of Quraysh were gathered there.
He recited Sūrat al-Najm (Chapter 53) aloud.
He prostrated at the concluding verse (53:62).
Authentic narrations mention that the Muslims who were present prostrated with him.
Authentic narrations mention that many of the disbelievers who heard the recitation also prostrated.
According to early reports, word reached the emigrants in Abyssinia that many—or all—of the people of Makkah had bowed with the Prophet.
Some of the emigrants set out from Abyssinia to return to Makkah based on this news.
When they were close to Makkah—about an hour’s distance—they learned that Quraysh had not embraced Islam.
Some of them chose to return again to Abyssinia.
Others entered Makkah quietly, either under the protection of a nobleman from among Quraysh or secretly.
Early Sīrah sources describe the subsequent departure as the second migration to Abyssinia.
Reports mention that their number reached over eighty men, not counting women and children.
There is a difference in the reports as to whether ‘Ammār ibn Yāsir was among those who migrated at this stage.
Quraysh tried to monitor and obstruct the departure of Muslims.
The Messenger of Allah remained in Makkah with those who had not migrated.`,
