    statementOfFactsText: `A group of Muslims had found safety in Abyssinia.
According to early Seerah accounts, Quraysh agreed to send two men as envoys to the Negus (al-Najāshī), the king of Abyssinia, to seek the extradition of the Muslims.
They chose ‘Amr ibn al-‘Āṣ and ‘Abdullāh ibn Abī Rabī‘ah as envoys.
They prepared gifts to present to the king and to some of his bishops and courtiers.
When the envoys arrived in Abyssinia, they presented their gifts.
The envoys asked that the Muslims be expelled and handed back to them.
The Negus refused to act merely on the word of the envoys.
The Negus summoned the Muslim emigrants to his court.
The Negus asked the Muslims about their religion and why they had come to his land.
Ja‘far ibn Abī Ṭālib is reported to have spoken on behalf of the Muslims before the Negus.
The Negus asked them if they had anything from the revelation that their Prophet recited to them.
Reports mention that Ja‘far recited from Sūrat Maryam.
Sūrat Maryam contains the story of Zakariyyā, Yaḥyā, Maryam, and ‘Īsā.
The Negus declared that he would not hand the Muslims over to their enemies.
The Negus granted the emigrants safety and freedom in his land.
The Negus returned the gifts to the envoys of Quraysh and refused their request.
The next day, the envoys approached the king again.
The Negus summoned the Muslims again and asked them about what they said concerning ‘Īsā ibn Maryam.
The Negus confirmed his protection of the Muslims.
The Negus ordered that the Muslims remain in his land in security.
The Negus refused to accept the gifts brought by ‘Amr and his companion.
The envoys returned to Makkah without achieving their aim.
The Muslims lived in Abyssinia in safety for a number of years.
Many of the Muslims later joined Muhammad in Madinah after the Hijrah.
News reached Quraysh that their envoys had failed.
Abū Ṭālib was Muhammad’s uncle.
Abū Ṭālib held a respected position among Quraysh.
The chiefs of Quraysh approached Abū Ṭālib repeatedly.
They insisted that he restrain Muhammad and warned that if he did not, they would confront both of them with open hostility.
According to early Seerah reports, Abū Ṭālib called Muhammad and spoke to him about the increasing pressure from Quraysh.
Abū Ṭālib assured Muhammad that he would not surrender him to their enemies.
Abū Ṭālib composed lines of poetry supporting his nephew.`,
