    statementOfFactsText: `They came to Abū Ṭālib bringing with them a young man from Quraysh, ‘Amārah ibn al-Walīd ibn al-Mughīrah.
They proposed that Abū Ṭālib take ‘Amārah ibn al-Walīd ibn al-Mughīrah as a son in place of Muhammad.
Abū Ṭālib rejected this offer.
Abū Ṭālib refused to surrender Muhammad to them.
These approaches and discussions with Abū Ṭālib took place in the Makkan phase after the call had become public.
Many of the chiefs of Quraysh began to discuss openly the idea of killing Muhammad.
Ḥamzah ibn ‘Abd al-Muṭṭalib embraced Islam.
‘Umar ibn al-Khaṭṭāb embraced Islam.
Many attempts to harm Muhammad took place in or near the Sacred Mosque while he was praying or reciting the Qur’an.
In one incident narrated by Ibn Mas‘ūd in Ṣaḥīḥ al-Bukhārī, the filth of a slaughtered animal was placed on Muhammad’s back while he was in sujūd.
Fāṭimah removed the filth from his back in that incident.
In another incident narrated in Ṣaḥīḥ al-Bukhārī, ‘Uqbah ibn Abī Mu‘ayṭ put his garment around Muhammad’s neck while he was praying in the Ḥijr of the Ka‘bah and strangled him severely.
Abū Bakr seized ‘Uqbah by the shoulder and pushed him away in that incident.
Ibn Isḥāq relates that Abū Jahl declared he would take a large stone and crush Muhammad’s head when he prostrated in prayer.
Those present approved of Abū Jahl’s plan and encouraged him.
On the following day, Abū Jahl waited for Muhammad near the Ka‘bah with a heavy rock in his hand.
As Muhammad went into sujūd, Abū Jahl advanced with the stone.
According to authentic narrations, when he drew near he turned back, his face changed, and his hands trembled until the stone fell from them.
Abū Jahl said he had seen between himself and Muhammad a barrier and a terrifying apparition that prevented him from approaching.
A narration from ‘Abdullāh ibn ‘Amr ibn al-‘Āṣ relates that some men of Quraysh were sitting in al-Ḥijr near the Ka‘bah.
Muhammad came and began to circumambulate the House.
He passed them twice without responding.
On the third time, he stopped.`,
