    statementOfFactsText: `Hamzah ibn Abd al Muttalib accepted Islam.
Umar ibn al Khattab accepted Islam.
A group of the leading men of Makkah gathered in the enclosure of the Kabah.
Among them was Utbah ibn Rabiah.
They agreed to send someone to speak with Muhammad.
They intended to offer him wealth, status, or leadership if he would leave off criticizing their idols and their way.
They agreed that Utbah should go to him and present their proposal.
Utbah went to the Messenger of Allah while he was sitting near the Kabah.
Utbah offered that if he desired wealth, they would gather for him the greatest riches among Quraysh.
Utbah offered that if he sought honor, they would make him their chief.
Utbah offered that if he wanted rule, they would not decide any matter without him.
The Messenger of Allah recited from the beginning of Surah Fussilat (41 1 5).
He continued to recite until he reached the verse, “So if they turn away, then say, I have warned you of a thunderbolt like the thunderbolt that struck Ad and Thamud.” (41 13)
He continued until he reached the sajdah and prostrated.
After the recitation and prostration, the Messenger of Allah told Utbah that he had heard his reply and that he could now do as he wished.
Utbah returned to his people.
Another narration relates that when the Messenger of Allah reached the verse (41 13), Utbah asked him to stop.
He then hastened back to Quraysh.
There was an attempt to barter Muhammad for a youth of Quraysh.
Abu Jahl attempted to crush Muhammad with a stone while he was praying.
Uqbah ibn Abi Muit tried to strangle Muhammad.
Before his Islam, Umar intended to kill Muhammad.
The leaders of shirk began to discuss plans to kill the Messenger of Allah and to coordinate among themselves.
Abu Talib gathered Bani Hashim and Bani al Muttalib, the descendants of Abd Manaf.
Abu Talib called them to support and protect Muhammad.
They agreed to stand with him in protecting Muhammad.
Abu Lahab refused and sided with the idolaters.`,
