    statementOfFactsText: `Quraysh ended the formal boycott.
Abu Talib was an elderly man.
Not long after the boycott ended, Abu Talib was struck by a persistent illness.
The leaders of Quraysh decided to try one more round of negotiation.
Their aim was to push Abu Talib to get his nephew to accept some form of compromise and to give up openly condemning their idols.
According to early seerah reports, a delegation of Quraysh went to visit Abu Talib while he was ill.
The delegation included Utbah bin Rabiah.
The delegation included Shaybah bin Rabiah.
The delegation included Abu Jahl bin Hisham.
The delegation included Umayyah bin Khalaf.
The delegation included Abu Sufyan bin Harb.
The delegation proposed that they would leave Muhammad and his religion alone if he would leave them and their religion alone.
The delegation proposed that Muhammad stop speaking against their gods and their way.
Abu Talib sent for his nephew and told him what they had said.
Abu Talib indicated that these were the leading men of his people.
Abu Talib indicated that they had come offering a policy of mutual non-interference and coexistence.
The Messenger of Allah said, “I will guide you to a matter by which you will gain authority over the Arabs and the non-Arabs.”
In another report, he addressed Abu Talib and said, “O uncle, why do you not call them to a word that is better for them?”
Abu Talib asked him, “What is this matter to which you invite them?”
The Prophet replied that it was a single word which, if they accepted it, would grant them leadership over the Arabs and make the non-Arabs submit under their authority.
Abu Jahl said, “What is this word? By your father, we will give you that and ten times more.”
The Prophet said, “Say, ‘There is no god but Allah,’ and abandon all that you worship besides Him.”
When they heard this, they clapped their hands.
When they heard this, they rejected the proposal.`,
