    statementOfFactsText: `In the thirteenth year of Prophethood, during the pilgrimage season, a group of Muslims from Madinah came with their people to Makkah to perform the rites of Hajj.
They were more than seventy in number from the Aws and Khazraj who had already embraced Islam.
They established secret contact with the Messenger of Allah and agreed with him to meet by night, in secrecy, during the days of Tashriq, at the same place as the previous year near the hill of Aqabah.
Kaab bin Malik al Ansari said in meaning that they set a time for the meeting in the middle of the nights of Tashriq.
With them on the journey was a respected elder, Abdullah bin Amr bin Haram.
According to the seerah reports, Abdullah bin Amr bin Haram accepted Islam and attended the meeting at Aqabah that night.
When about one third of the night had passed, they gathered on the hill near Aqabah.
They were seventy three men and two women.
The two women were Nusaybah bint Kab of Banu Najjar and Asma bint Amr of Banu Salamah.
The Messenger of Allah arrived accompanied by his uncle al Abbas bin Abdul Muttalib.
At that time al Abbas was not yet a Muslim.
Al Abbas bin Abdul Muttalib spoke first to the people of Yathrib.
The two women present gave their pledge verbally, as the Prophet did not take women’s pledges by hand.
The Messenger of Allah requested that they appoint from among themselves twelve representatives to carry responsibility among their people in Madinah.
They chose twelve men.
From the Khazraj, they chose Asad bin Zurarah bin Udas.
From the Khazraj, they chose Sad bin ar Rabi bin Amr.
From the Khazraj, they chose Abdullah bin Rawahah bin Thalabah.
From the Khazraj, they chose Rafi bin Malik bin al Ajlan.
From the Khazraj, they chose Al Bara bin Marur bin Sakhr.
From the Khazraj, they chose Abdullah bin Amr bin Haram.
From the Khazraj, they chose Ubada bin as Samit bin Qais.
From the Khazraj, they chose Sad bin Ubada bin Dulaym.
From the Khazraj, they chose al Mundhir bin Amr bin Khunays.
From the Aws, they chose Usayd bin Hudayr bin Samak.
From the Aws, they chose Sad bin Khaythamah bin al Harith.
From the Aws, they chose Rifaa bin Abdul Mundhir bin Zubair.
They were made responsible over their people concerning this pledge.
Reports reached Quraysh that Muhammad had met a group from Yathrib at night.
The Messenger of Allah instructed the Ansar to return to their camps.
Some of them offered to attack the people of Mina with the sword if he wished.
In the morning, a group of the chiefs of Quraysh came to the camps of the people of Yathrib.
The polytheists of Madinah swore by Allah that no such thing had occurred.
Abdullah bin Ubayy bin Sulul denied that his people had done anything without his knowledge.
The Muslims from Madinah kept silent and did not reveal the matter.
The Quraysh delegation returned to Makkah.
After the pilgrims had left, Quraysh became certain that a pledge had in fact been made.
Quraysh pursued the caravan of the Ansar.
They caught only Sad bin Ubadah.
They seized Sad bin Ubadah and subjected him to beating and rough treatment.
He was rescued by al Mutim bin Adi and Harith bin Harb bin Umayyah.
Al Mutim bin Adi and Harith bin Harb bin Umayyah had ties with Sad bin Ubadah through trade.
They secured his release.
This was the Second Aqabah Pledge.
It was known as the Great Aqabah Pledge.`,
