    statementOfFactsText: `After the Second Aqabah Pledge, the Messenger of Allah gave permission for the believers in Makkah to migrate to Madinah.
According to early seerah reports, the first to migrate to Madinah was Abu Salamah, about a year before the Great Aqabah Pledge.
When Abu Salamah resolved to leave Makkah, his wife’s family detained her and took hold of their child.
In the struggle, Umm Salamah’s arm was injured.
Abu Salamah left for Madinah alone.
Umm Salamah was kept in Makkah, separated from both husband and child.
She was later released along with her child to rejoin her husband.
On the way to Madinah, Uthman bin Talhah, a man from Quraysh, met her and escorted her.
She reached her husband in the area of Quba, on the outskirts of Madinah.
Suhayb agreed to give up his wealth in return for being allowed to leave Makkah.
Umar ibn al Khattab, Ayyash ibn Abi Rabiah, and Hisham ibn al As agreed to meet in the morning at a certain place to leave together for Madinah.
Umar and Ayyash arrived at the meeting place, but Hisham was prevented from leaving by his people.
Abu Jahl and his brother Harith went to Madinah and met Ayyash.
They urged Ayyash to return to Makkah, claiming his mother had vowed not to comb her hair or seek shade until she saw him again.
Umar warned Ayyash not to go and lent him a strong camel.
Ayyash decided to return to Makkah.
Umar advised Ayyash to stay on the camel and be cautious.
As they traveled back, Abu Jahl complained of his mount and asked to ride behind Ayyash.
When the camels were made to kneel, Abu Jahl and Harith seized Ayyash, tied him, and took him back to Makkah.
Ayyash was imprisoned in Makkah and pressured about his faith.
Those who remained in Makkah were the Messenger of Allah, Abu Bakr, Ali ibn Abi Talib, and a number of believers who were held back or were unable to migrate.
Reports mention that many of those who had migrated earlier to Abyssinia later joined the Muslims in Madinah.
Abu Bakr prepared two strong camels and fed them specially for months for the journey.
The chiefs of Quraysh convened in Dar al Nadwah, their council house in Makkah, shortly before the Hijrah.
Attendees included Abu Jahl ibn Hisham from Banu Makhzum.
Attendees included Jubayr ibn Mutim and others from Banu Nawfal.
Attendees included Abu Sufyan ibn Harb from Banu Abd Shams.
Attendees included Utbah and Shaybah, the sons of Rabiah, from Banu Abd Shams.
Attendees included Nadr ibn al Harith from Banu Abd ad Dar.
Attendees included Abu al Bukhtari ibn Hisham from Banu Asad ibn Abd al Uzza.
Attendees included Zamah ibn al Aswad from Banu Asad ibn Abd al Uzza.
Attendees included Hakim ibn Hizam from Banu Asad ibn Abd al Uzza.
Attendees included Nabih and Munbih, the two sons of Hajjaj, from Banu Sahm.
Attendees included Umayyah ibn Khalaf from Banu Jumah.
An unknown elderly man from the region of Najd attended the meeting after asking to sit with them.
One proposal discussed was to imprison Muhammad in Makkah.
Another proposal discussed was to expel Muhammad from Makkah.
Abu Jahl proposed selecting young men from all the main clans of Quraysh to strike Muhammad together with their swords at a single moment.
According to the seerah, they agreed on Abu Jahl’s plan.
Madinah occupied a position on the trade routes to the north.
Quraysh depended heavily on their caravans for their livelihood.
Muhammad was being welcomed by the tribes of Aws and Khazraj.`,
