    statementOfFactsText: `At midday the Prophet [pbuh] went, with his face covered, to the house of Abu Bakr [R] at an unusual hour.
That night the clans of Quraysh surrounded the house of the Prophet [pbuh] and kept watch at his door until dawn.
Reports mention that the Prophet [pbuh] was inside with Ali ibn Abi Talib [R].
He told Ali ibn Abi Talib [R] to sleep in his bed and to cover himself with his cloak.
The Prophet [pbuh] left his house and went to the house of Abu Bakr [R].
Abu Bakr [R] set out with him, and they headed south, in the opposite direction of the usual road to Madinah.
They climbed to the cave of Thawr to hide there.
When the besiegers entered the house at dawn, they found Ali [R] in the Prophet’s bed instead of Muhammad [pbuh].
The Prophet [pbuh] left his house on the 27th of Safar in the fourteenth year of Prophethood.
The two companions walked until they reached Mount Thawr, south of Makkah.
The path to Mount Thawr was difficult and rocky.
Abu Bakr [R] entered the cave first to check it.
The Prophet [pbuh] then entered the cave.
They stayed in the cave for three nights.
Abdullah, the son of Abu Bakr, would come to them in the evening.
He spent part of the night with them.
He informed them of Quraysh’s movements in Makkah.
He returned before dawn.
Amir ibn Fuhayrah, their freedman, used to bring a flock of sheep to the area after Abdullah left.
They could drink fresh milk.
Abu Bakr [R] arranged with a guide, Abdullah ibn Uraiqit, who had expert knowledge of the routes.
Abdullah ibn Uraiqit had not embraced Islam yet.
Abu Bakr [R] hired Abdullah ibn Uraiqit to lead them on a special route after those three nights.
Quraysh intensified their search.
Quraysh blocked the main routes.
Quraysh sent out trackers to follow possible trails.
Quraysh set a large reward for anyone who could capture the Prophet [pbuh] or Abu Bakr [R].
The trackers reached the mouth of the cave where the two companions were hiding.
After three nights in the cave, Abdullah ibn Uraiqit arrived with Abu Bakr’s two camels.
Abu Bakr [R] brought the camels he had prepared earlier.
The Prophet [pbuh] chose one of the camels and accepted to ride it on the condition that he would pay its price.
They took provisions that Asma bint Abi Bakr [R] had tied in her waist-wrapper.
She tore off a piece of her waist-wrapper to tie the food.
She became known as “the one of the two waist-wrappers.”
The Prophet [pbuh], Abu Bakr [R], and Amir ibn Fuhayrah set out with Abdullah ibn Uraiqit guiding them.
They followed paths rarely used.
They followed the coastal route rather than the direct caravan road.
This was in Rabi al Awwal, in the first year after the Hijrah, corresponding to the year 622 of the common era.
On the road, they passed by scattered settlements and tents.
Under the intense heat, Abu Bakr [R] found a small shaded place near a rock.
He met a shepherd and requested some milk.
He brought milk to the Prophet [pbuh] and cooled it with water.
Some people went out specifically to search for the Prophet [pbuh] because of the promised reward.
Among them was Suraqah ibn Malik.
Information reached Suraqah ibn Malik that a small group had been seen travelling along an unusual route.
Suraqah ibn Malik followed them.
Suraqah ibn Malik came close to them.
Suraqah ibn Malik informed them of Quraysh’s reward and asked for assurance.
The Prophet [pbuh] gave Suraqah ibn Malik safety and a written guarantee.
Suraqah ibn Malik was asked to conceal their route from their pursuers.
Suraqah ibn Malik returned and turned away others who were searching.
They continued northwards until they reached the area of some tents belonging to Umm Ma’bad al Khuza’iyyah.
They asked Umm Ma’bad for food and milk.
It was a time of drought.
The travellers met az Zubayr ibn al Awwam returning from Syria with a trade caravan.
Az Zubayr ibn al Awwam gave the Prophet [pbuh] and Abu Bakr [R] two white garments.
On Monday, the 8th of Rabi al Awwal in the fourteenth year of Prophethood, corresponding to the first year after the Hijrah, the Prophet [pbuh] reached Quba on the outskirts of Madinah.
Quba was a village inhabited by the tribe of Amr ibn Awf.
The Prophet [pbuh] stayed in Quba as a guest of Kulthum ibn al Hadm.
He remained in Quba for four days: Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday.
During this time, he and the Muslims laid the foundations of the mosque at Quba.
Ali ibn Abi Talib [R] remained in Makkah for a short period to return the trusts to their owners.
Ali ibn Abi Talib [R] set out on his migration to join the Prophet [pbuh] in Quba.
Ali ibn Abi Talib [R] arrived in Quba.
On Friday morning, the Prophet [pbuh] sent for the clan of Banu an Najjar.
The clan of Banu an Najjar came to escort him into Madinah.
He rode on his camel, and Abu Bakr [R] rode with him.
He stopped in the valley of Banu Salim ibn Awf and led the first Friday prayer there with a group of Muslims.
The camel knelt in the area belonging to Banu an Najjar, near the place where the Prophet’s mosque would later be built.
The Prophet [pbuh] dismounted there and said that this would be his place.
The nearest house belonged to Abu Ayyub al Ansari [R].
Abu Ayyub al Ansari [R] took the Prophet’s belongings.
The Prophet [pbuh] stayed in the house of Abu Ayyub al Ansari [R].
The Prophet [pbuh] remained there until his mosque and living quarters were built.
After some time, Sawdah bint Zam’ah [R] arrived in Madinah.
His daughters Fatimah and Umm Kulthum [R] arrived in Madinah.
Usamah ibn Zayd and Umm Ayman arrived in Madinah.
The family of Abu Bakr [R] arrived, including his wife and his daughter Aishah [R].
His daughter Zaynab [R] remained in Makkah with her husband Abul As ibn ar Rabi until after the Battle of Badr.
When the Prophet [pbuh] arrived in Madinah, the climate of the city affected Abu Bakr [R] and Bilal [R], and they became ill with fever.
Aishah [R] tended to Abu Bakr [R] and Bilal [R] during their illness.`,
