    statementOfFactsText: `The first phase extended from the Hijrah until the Treaty of al-Hudaybiyah in Dhul-Qaʿdah of the sixth year after Hijrah.
The second phase extended from the Treaty of al-Hudaybiyah until the conquest of Makkah in Ramaḍān of the eighth year after Hijrah.
The third phase extended from the conquest of Makkah until the death of the Prophet in Rabīʿ al-Awwal of the eleventh year after Hijrah.
During the second phase, there was a truce with the major pagan leadership in Arabia.
During the second phase, the Prophet sent letters and messengers to kings and rulers beyond Arabia.
During the third phase, delegations came to Madinah from across Arabia.
In Madinah, the Prophet was faced with three main categories of people: the Muslims, the remaining polytheists from among the people of Madinah, and the Jews.
The Muslims in Madinah consisted essentially of two groups.
The first group were the Ansar, the original inhabitants of Madinah from al-Aws and al-Khazraj.
The Ansar had homes, land, and wealth.
The second group were the Muhajirun, those who had left their homes and wealth in Makkah.
Most of the Muhajirun arrived in Madinah with little or no material resources.
Their numbers increased after the Prophet permitted migration.
ʿAbdullah ibn Ubayy ibn Salul outwardly professed Islam and joined the Muslim ranks.
The Jews had settled in the Hijaz generations earlier.
The Jews in and around Madinah spoke Arabic, dressed like the Arabs, and lived among them.
There were cases of intermarriage between the Jews and the surrounding Arabs.
The Jews would refer to the Arabs as “ummi” (unlettered).
In livelihood the Jews were active in trade, agriculture-related commerce, and lending with interest.
The Jews had dealings with some of the Arab leaders and landowners.
Three major Jewish tribes lived in and around Madinah: Banu Qaynuqaʿ, Banu al-Nadir, and Banu Qurayzah.
Banu Qaynuqaʿ were allied with al-Khazraj.
Banu al-Nadir and Banu Qurayzah were closer to al-Aws.
According to early seerah reports, Safiyyah bint Huyayy said that news reached her father Huyayy ibn Akhtab and her uncle Abu Yasir of the arrival of the Messenger at Quba with Banu ʿAmr ibn ʿAwf.
According to early seerah reports, Huyayy ibn Akhtab and Abu Yasir went out early to look at him and did not return until sunset.
ʿAbdullah ibn Salam had been a leading rabbi among the Jews of Madinah.
When the Prophet arrived in Madinah, ʿAbdullah ibn Salam came to him, asked him questions, and accepted Islam.
ʿAbdullah ibn Salam said to the Prophet that if his people knew of his Islam, they would speak ill of him.
The Prophet sent for some of the Jewish elders and asked them about ʿAbdullah ibn Salam, and they praised him as their scholar and a man of good standing.
ʿAbdullah ibn Salam then informed them that he had believed in the Messenger of Allah, and they spoke against him and accused him.
This was the first direct interaction of the Prophet with a group from among the Jews after his arrival in Madinah.
After the Hijrah, the Quraysh seized the property left behind by the emigrants.
After the Hijrah, the Quraysh detained some of the emigrants’ families.
The Quraysh continued to incite the Arab tribes against the Muslims.
The Quraysh worked toward isolating Madinah socially and economically.`,
