    statementOfFactsText: `Muslims began practical military activity in the form of small patrols and expeditions.
Their tasks were to observe the routes around Madīnah and those leading toward Makkah.
Their tasks included becoming familiar with the terrain.
Their tasks included establishing understandings with tribes near those routes.
In Ramaḍān of year 1 A.H., the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] sent Ḥamzah ibn ʿAbd al-Muṭṭalib [R] at the head of around thirty Emigrants toward Sīf al-Baḥr.
The aim of the detachment to Sīf al-Baḥr was to intercept a caravan of Quraysh.
Sīf al-Baḥr is a coastal area.
Reports mention that the caravan was led by Abū Jahl ibn Hishām.
The two parties faced one another and formed up, but fighting did not occur.
Majdī ibn ʿAmr intervened and calmed the situation.
Majdī ibn ʿAmr had ties with both sides.
Reports state that the Prophet [pbuh] gave this detachment a white banner to carry.
In Shawwāl of year 1 A.H., the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] dispatched ʿUbaydah ibn al-Ḥārith ibn al-Muṭṭalib [R] with a group of around sixty Emigrants toward Baṭn Rābiġ.
At Baṭn Rābiġ they encountered a caravan of Quraysh in which Abū Sufyān ibn Ḥarb was present.
Some arrows were shot between the two sides, but there was no close combat.
On this occasion al-Miqdād ibn ʿAmr and ʿUtbah ibn Ghazwān [R] left Quraysh and joined the Muslims.
Reports mention that their banner was white and carried by Miṣṭaḥ ibn Uthāthah.
In Dhū al-Qaʿdah of year 1 A.H., the Prophet [pbuh] sent Saʿd ibn Abī Waqqāṣ [R] with about twenty men and instructed them not to go beyond al-Kharrār.
After several days of travel they reached al-Kharrār but the Quraysh caravan had already passed.
Reports state that they carried a white banner, borne by al-Miqdād ibn ʿAmr.
In Ṣafar of year 2 A.H., the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] went out in person with a small group, mostly Emigrants, toward al-Abwāʾ/Waddān to intercept a Quraysh caravan.
He appointed Saʿd ibn ʿUbādah [R] over Madīnah in his absence.
No caravan was encountered during this expedition.
A non-aggression agreement was concluded with ʿAmr ibn Makshī of Banū Ḍamrah.
This was the first campaign in which the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] personally led a detachment.
Reports mention that its banner was white and carried by Ḥamzah ibn ʿAbd al-Muṭṭalib.
In Rabīʿ al-Awwal of year 2 A.H., the Prophet [pbuh] set out with a group of Companions toward Buwāṭ to intercept a trading caravan of Quraysh.
Among the caravan were several of their notable men, among them Umayyah ibn Khalaf.
He appointed Saʿd ibn Muʿādh [R] over Madīnah while he was away.
When the Muslims reached Buwāṭ, the caravan had already moved on, and they returned without engagement.
Also in Rabīʿ al-Awwal of year 2 A.H., a small party of idolaters led by Kurz ibn Jābir raided the pastures of Madīnah and drove off some animals belonging to the Muslims.
The Prophet [pbuh] went out with around seventy men in pursuit and followed them toward Safawān, near Badr, but did not catch them.
This expedition was later referred to as the First Badr or Badr al-Ūlā.
During this absence, the Prophet [pbuh] left Zayd ibn Ḥārithah [R] in charge of Madīnah.
Reports state that the standard for this expedition was white, carried by ʿAlī ibn Abī Ṭālib [R].
In Jumādā al-Ūlā and Jumādā al-Ākhirah of year 2 A.H., the Prophet [pbuh] set out with about one hundred to two hundred men with a limited number of camels that they rode in turns, moving toward Dhū al-ʿUshayrah in the region of Yanbuʿ.
The purpose was to intercept a Quraysh caravan traveling to Syria.
When they reached Dhū al-ʿUshayrah, the caravan had already passed several days earlier.
This was the same caravan whose return journey from Syria later became the direct cause for the Battle of Badr.
A non-aggression understanding was concluded with Banū Mudlij and their allies from Banū Ḍamrah.
The Prophet [pbuh] appointed Abū Salamah ibn ʿAbd al-Asad [R] to oversee Madīnah in his absence.
In Rajab of year 2 A.H., the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] sent ʿAbdullāh ibn Jaḥsh al-Asadī [R] with a small party of Emigrants toward Nakhlah, a valley between Makkah and Ṭāʾif.
He gave him a written instruction and told him not to read it until he had traveled for two days.
After two days of travel, ʿAbdullāh ibn Jaḥsh opened the letter and found the order to proceed to Nakhlah and observe Quraysh, gathering information about their movements.
He informed his companions of what the Prophet [pbuh] had written, and they agreed to continue.
At Nakhlah, a caravan of Quraysh passed by carrying goods such as raisins and other merchandise.
Among those with the caravan were ʿAmr ibn al-Ḥaḍramī and ʿUthmān and Nawfal, the sons of ʿAbdullāh ibn al-Mughīrah.
Some of the Muslims attacked, ʿAmr ibn al-Ḥaḍramī was struck and killed, two men from the caravan were captured, and one escaped.
The Muslims took some of the caravan’s goods and returned to Madīnah.
When they came to the Prophet [pbuh], he did not approve what had been done in the sacred month and held off making any ruling regarding the goods and the captives.
Quraysh accused the Muslims of violating what was inviolable and shedding blood in a sacred month.
Later, the two captives were released.
Compensation was given for the slain man according to what was agreed.
Rajab was regarded by the Arabs as one of the sacred months during which fighting was customarily avoided.
In Shaʿbān of 2 A.H., the qiblah was changed from Bayt al-Maqdis (Jerusalem) to al-Masjid al-Ḥarām in Makkah.`,
