    statementOfFactsText: `During the expedition of Dhū al-‘Ushayrah, a major Quraysh caravan passed safely.
The Prophet and his Companions were unable to intercept that caravan.
The caravan returning from Syria was led by Abū Sufyān ibn Ḥarb.
The Prophet sent Ṭalḥah ibn ‘Ubaydillāh and Sa‘īd ibn Zayd northward to observe the route.
Ṭalḥah ibn ‘Ubaydillāh and Sa‘īd ibn Zayd remained at al-Ḥawrā’ for some days.
Abū Sufyān passed by al-Ḥawrā’ with the caravan.
Ṭalḥah ibn ‘Ubaydillāh and Sa‘īd ibn Zayd returned to Madīnah and informed the Prophet.
The Prophet called upon the Muslims to go out toward the caravan and made it optional.
Slightly more than three hundred men set out, including Emigrants and Helpers from Aws and Khazraj.
They had around seventy camels.
Two or three men shared each camel.
The Prophet, ‘Alī ibn Abī Ṭālib, and Murthid ibn Abī Murthid al-Ghanawī shared one mount.
The Prophet first left Ibn Umm Maktūm in charge of the prayers and affairs of Madīnah.
The Prophet later appointed Abū Lubābah ibn ‘Abd al-Mundhir in charge of Madīnah.
The general standard was white.
The general standard was borne by Muṣ‘ab ibn ‘Umayr al-Qurashī al-‘Abdarī.
The Emigrants formed one battalion with their standard carried by ‘Alī ibn Abī Ṭālib.
The Helpers formed another battalion with their standard in the hand of Sa‘d ibn Mu‘ādh.
Among the commanders of the flanks were al-Zubayr ibn al-‘Awwām and al-Miqdād ibn ‘Amr.
A rear-guard was assigned.
The Prophet was the overall commander of the force.
The Prophet marched along the main road toward Makkah.
The Prophet then turned left toward the region of Badr.
When he reached al-Ṣafrā’, he sent out scouts to gather information about the caravan.
Abū Sufyān altered his route toward the coastal path near the Red Sea.
Abū Sufyān passed safely beyond the reach of the Muslim detachment.
Abū Sufyān dispatched Damdām ibn ‘Amr al-Ghifārī to Makkah to seek support.
The messenger arrived in Makkah warning that Muhammad and his Companions were heading toward the caravan.
Quraysh mobilized fighters from most of the major clans.
Quraysh called upon some of their Arab allies.
Banū ‘Adī held back.
A large force set out from Makkah including many chiefs and notables.
Word reached them from Abū Sufyān that he had safely diverted the caravan.
Many among Quraysh proposed to turn back.
Abū Jahl ibn Hishām insisted on continuing toward Badr.
Banū Zuhrah withdrew upon the advice of al-Akhnas ibn Shurayq.
Others continued with Abū Jahl until approximately one thousand men remained.
They camped on the higher side of the valley of Badr at al-‘Udwah al-Quswā.
News of the Quraysh force reached the Prophet.
The Prophet consulted his Companions.
Abū Bakr and ‘Umar spoke affirming readiness.
Al-Miqdād ibn ‘Amr expressed firm support.
The Prophet sought the opinion of the Helpers regarding fighting outside Madīnah.
Sa‘d ibn Mu‘ādh spoke reaffirming their pledge to obey.
Near Badr, the Prophet and Abū Bakr went ahead of the army and gathered information about Quraysh.
They questioned travelers and water-carriers.
They estimated the approximate number of the Makkan force from the number of animals being slaughtered per day.
They confirmed the composition of the Makkan force from the names of their leading men.
The Prophet informed his Companions that Quraysh had sent forth their best men.
That night, rain fell.
The Muslims advanced and camped closer to the wells of Badr.
Al-Ḥubāb ibn al-Mundhir asked whether the position was chosen by revelation or military judgment.
The Prophet answered that it was judgment and consultation.
Al-Ḥubāb suggested moving to the nearest well to the enemy, building a reservoir, and rendering the other wells unusable.
The Prophet accepted the suggestion.
The Muslims moved and prepared their position near the water.
Sa‘d ibn Mu‘ādh proposed building a shelter on an elevated spot for the Prophet.
A small group from the Helpers was assigned to guard the Prophet at the shelter.
The shelter was constructed.
On the night before the battle, many of the Muslims slept.
At dawn, the Prophet led them in prayer.
As the sun rose, he arranged their ranks.
Quraysh drew up their formations opposite the Muslims at al-‘Udwah al-Quswā.
Reconnaissance by ‘Umayr ibn Wahb al-Jumahī indicated to Quraysh that the Muslims were around three hundred men.
The Prophet ordered his Companions not to begin fighting until he gave the word.
The Prophet instructed his Companions to use their arrows carefully.
The Prophet forbade his Companions from rushing out rashly.
The first individual to advance against the Muslims’ water-reservoir was al-Aswad ibn ‘Abd al-Asad al-Makhzūmī.
Ḥamzah ibn ‘Abd al-Muṭṭalib struck down al-Aswad near the basin.
‘Utbah ibn Rabī‘ah, his brother Shaybah, and his son al-Walīd came forth and called for counterparts to duel.
Three young men from the Helpers stepped out.
The Quraysh demanded peers from the same tribe.
The Prophet sent ‘Ubaydah ibn al-Ḥārith, Ḥamzah, and ‘Alī ibn Abī Ṭālib.
In the duels, Ḥamzah killed Shaybah.
In the duels, ‘Alī killed al-Walīd.
In the duels, ‘Ubaydah and ‘Utbah exchanged severe blows.
Ḥamzah and ‘Alī helped finish ‘Utbah.
Ḥamzah and ‘Alī carried ‘Ubaydah, wounded, back to the Muslim lines.
‘Ubaydah ibn al-Ḥārith later died from his wound on the way back to Madīnah.
After the duels, the main engagement commenced.
The Prophet threw dust toward the enemy.
Many of Quraysh’s leading men were killed.
Among those who fell were ‘Utbah, Shaybah, and al-Walīd.
Abū Jahl tried to rally the ranks when the army scattered.
Mu‘ādh ibn ‘Amr ibn al-Jamūḥ and Mu‘ādh ibn ‘Afrā’ struck down Abū Jahl.
After the fighting, ‘Abdullāh ibn Mas‘ūd found Abū Jahl still alive and finished him.
‘Abdullāh ibn Mas‘ūd brought the news to the Prophet.
The battle ended in a victory for the Muslims on the seventeenth of Ramaḍān in the second year after the Hijrah.`,
