    statementOfFactsText: `Among those most insistent on preparing for war were Ikrimah bin Abi Jahl, Safwan bin Umayyah, Abu Sufyan bin Harb, and Abdullah bin Abi Rabiah.
They sent emissaries to allied tribes and sought the help of groups from Kinana, the people of the Tihamah region, and the Ahabish.
Quraysh’s trade caravans went in the summer to Syria and in the winter to Yemen.
They decided that the profits of the caravan led by Abu Sufyan which had escaped at Badr would be devoted to equipping a new army.
They enlisted poets to incite the tribes against the Muslims.
Abu Azza al Jumahi had previously been captured at Badr and was released without ransom on condition that he would not stand against the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] again.
Various reports mention that Safwan bin Umayyah urged Abu Azza al Jumahi back into the ranks of Quraysh.
Abu Sufyan had seen his provisions thrown away in the expedition of As Sawiq.
There was a successful raid led by Zaid bin Harithah.
They decided to take some of their women along.
Reports mention that their army numbered about three thousand fighters.
Reports mention that around seven hundred wore coats of mail.
Reports mention that there were two hundred cavalry.
Reports mention that there were some three thousand camels.
Reports mention that they were accompanied by about fifteen women.
The overall command was given to Abu Sufyan bin Harb.
Khalid bin al Walid led the cavalry.
Ikrimah bin Abi Jahl assisted Khalid bin al Walid in leading the cavalry.
The banner was entrusted to the clan of Banu Abd ad Dar.
Al Abbas bin Abdul Muttalib was still in Makkah.
When the army set out, Al Abbas bin Abdul Muttalib sent a detailed written report to the Messenger of Allah [pbuh].
A messenger brought this letter to him while he was at the Mosque of Quba.
Ubayy bin Kab read the letter to him.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] instructed Ubayy bin Kab to keep its contents confidential.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] returned to Madinah and gathered the Muhajirun and Ansar.
A group of the Ansar volunteered to guard the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] and kept watch at his door through the night.
Among those mentioned in this role were Sad bin Muadh, Usaid bin Hudair, and Sad bin Ubadah.
Armed patrols moved around the entrances and roads leading into Madinah.
Small reconnaissance detachments were sent out to track the movements of the Makkan army.
The army of Quraysh advanced along its usual western route toward Madinah.
They reached the area of al Abwa.
Some reports mention that Hind bint Utbah, the wife of Abu Sufyan, suggested desecrating the grave of the Prophet’s mother at al Abwa, but the leaders refused.
They proceeded along Wadi al Aqeeq.
They turned toward Uhud.
They encamped at Ainain at the foot of Mount Uhud on Friday, the 6th of Shawwal, in the third year after the Hijrah.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] convened a council of the Muhajirun and Ansar.
Abdullah bin Ubayy bin Salul was the leader of the Khazraj.
Abdullah bin Ubayy bin Salul agreed with the view of remaining inside the city.
A number of companions urged that the Muslims should go out and meet the enemy outside Madinah.
Hamzah bin Abdul Muttalib was among the most insistent on going out to meet the enemy.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] agreed to the view of going out to meet the army of Quraysh.
It was decided that the Muslims would march out of Madinah and take up a defensive position near Mount Uhud.`,
