    statementOfFactsText: `The first to advance from the idolaters was the standard-bearer Talha bin Abi Talha al-Abdari.
The Muslims used to call him “the Ram of the Battalion.”
He came forward on a camel.
He called the Muslims to single combat.
Reports mention that az-Zubair bin al-Awwam stepped forward, leapt onto the camel, pulled him to the ground, and killed him with his sword.
After Talha’s death, the men of Banu Abd ad-Dar successively took up the banner.
His brother Uthman took it.
Hamzah bin Abd al-Muttalib struck him with a blow that killed him.
Then Abu Sa'd bin Abi Talha raised the standard.
Sa'd bin Abi Waqqas shot him in the throat with a deadly arrow.
Reports also mention that Abu Sa'd went out to challenge the Muslims.
Reports also mention that Ali bin Abi Talib went out to meet him.
Reports also mention that they exchanged two blows.
Reports also mention that Ali killed him.
Musafi' bin Talha then lifted the banner.
Asim bin Thabit bin Abi al-Aqlah shot him with an arrow and he fell.
After that, Kilab bin Talha picked it up.
Az-Zubair killed him.
Al-Jallas bin Talha carried it.
Talhah bin Ubaydillah struck him down.
Another report attributes his death to Asim bin Thabit.
Artat bin Sharhabil then took the standard.
Some said Ali killed him.
Others said Hamzah killed him.
Shurayh bin Qariz carried it next.
He was killed by Quzman.
Then Abu Zayd Amr bin Abd Manaf al-Abdari took the banner.
He was also killed by Quzman.
After him, a son of Sharhabil bin Hashim al-Abdari hoisted the standard.
He was likewise killed by Quzman.
In all, ten standard-bearers from Banu Abd ad-Dar were killed.
Their freed slave Sawab took the banner.
When his hand was cut off he knelt.
He pressed the banner to his chest and neck so that it would not fall.
He continued fighting until he was killed.
After his death the standard fell and lay on the ground.
No one remained to carry it.
Abu Dujanah was known by the red headband he wore in battle.
Az-Zubair said he followed Abu Dujanah.
Az-Zubair said he saw him tie on his red headband.
A man from the idolaters faced Abu Dujanah and they exchanged two blows.
The man’s strike lodged in Abu Dujanah’s leather shield.
Abu Dujanah struck him with the Prophet’s sword and killed him.
He then advanced toward a person who was urging the idolaters on and raised the sword over that person.
A cry was heard, and it turned out to be a woman.
The woman was Hind bint Utbah.
Az-Zubair said he saw Abu Dujanah lift the sword over the parting of Hind’s hair, then hold it back.
Wahshi bin Harb said he was a slave of Jubayr bin Mut'im.
Jubayr bin Mut'im’s uncle Tu'aymah bin Adi had been killed at Badr.
Jubayr said to Wahshi that if he killed Hamzah, in return for his uncle, he would be free.
When Quraysh marched to Uhud, Wahshi went out with the people.
Wahshi said he was skilled at throwing the spear.
When the two sides met, Wahshi looked for Hamzah.
He saw him among the fighters.
Wahshi hid behind a tree or a rock.
Then Siba' bin Abd al-Uzza came toward him.
Hamzah struck him with a blow.
Wahshi threw his spear at Hamzah.
It hit him in the lower abdomen and came out from between his legs.
He moved toward Wahshi but was overcome by his wound and fell.
Wahshi left him with the spear in him until he died.
Then Wahshi took his spear.
Wahshi went back to the camp.
Wahshi said he did not kill anyone else.
Wahshi said he only killed him so that he would be set free.
When he returned to Mecca, Wahshi had been set free.
Hanzalah al-Ghasil is Hanzalah bin Abi Amir.
He was newly married.
He left his wife and went straight out to the battle.
He reached Abu Sufyan Sakhr bin Harb.
Abu Sufyan Sakhr bin Harb was the leader of Quraysh.
Shaddad bin al-Aswad struck Hanzalah and killed him.`,
