    statementOfFactsText: `On Sunday morning, the day after Uhud, the 8th of Shawwal, 3 A.H., the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] called upon the people and ordered them to march out.
He said: “No one shall go out with us except those who participated in the battle of Uhud.”
‘Abdullah bin Ubayy said: “I will go out with you,” and the Prophet [pbuh] replied: “No.”
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] permitted Jabir bin ‘Abdullah to join Hamrā’ al-Asad.
The Muslims marched until they reached a place called Hamrā’ al-Asad, about eight miles from Madinah, and encamped there.
At Hamrā’ al-Asad, Ma‘bad bin Abī Ma‘bad from the tribe of Khuza‘ah came to the Messenger of Allah [pbuh].
Reports mention that Ma‘bad had embraced Islam; other reports state that he was still upon his people’s religion.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] directed Ma‘bad, according to reports, to go on and meet Abu Sufyan and his people.
The idolaters halted and encamped at ar-Rawha’, about thirty-six miles from Madinah.
Ma‘bad bin Abī Ma‘bad arrived in the Makkan camp.
The Quraysh decided to continue their withdrawal and return to Makkah.
A caravan from the tribe of ‘Abd al-Qays was passing by on its way to Madinah.
Abu Sufyan spoke to the ‘Abd al-Qays caravan to deliver a message to Muhammad.
Abu Sufyan promised the caravan loads of raisins at the market of ‘Ukaz in the coming year as payment for delivering the message.
The caravan reached Hamrā’ al-Asad and delivered Abu Sufyan’s message to the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] and the Muslims.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] remained encamped at Hamrā’ al-Asad for three days: Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday, the 9th to the 11th of Shawwal, 3 A.H.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] then returned with the Muslims to Madinah.
Before returning, the Muslims seized Abu ‘Azza al-Jumahi.
Abu ‘Azza al-Jumahi had been taken prisoner at Badr.
He had been released without ransom on the condition that he would never again fight against the Muslims nor assist their enemies.
Abu ‘Azza al-Jumahi went out with the idolaters at Uhud.
When he was captured again at Hamrā’ al-Asad, the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] ordered his execution, and he was put to death.
Mu‘awiyah bin al-Mughīrah bin Abī al-‘As, a man from Quraysh, came to Madinah after Uhud as a spy for the idolaters.
He went to his cousin ‘Uthman bin ‘Affan, who sheltered him with the permission of the Prophet [pbuh] on condition that he would leave Madinah within three days.
Mu‘awiyah remained beyond the three days and continued to gather news for Quraysh.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] sent Zayd bin Harithah and ‘Ammar bin Yasir in pursuit of Mu‘awiyah and ordered them to kill him if they found him.
Zayd bin Harithah and ‘Ammar bin Yasir caught up with Mu‘awiyah bin al-Mughīrah and killed him.`,
