    statementOfFactsText: `The archers whom the Messenger of Allah had placed on the hillside abandoned the position he had explicitly ordered them to hold until the end of the battle.
Soon after Uḥud, the tribe of Banu Asad prepared a raid against Madinah.
The people of ‘Udal and Qarah plotted against the Muslims in Safar, 4 A.H., resulting in the killing of a group of the Prophet’s Companions.
Banu ‘Amir were involved in events that led to the tragedy of Bi’r Ma‘unah, in which around seventy Qur’an-reciters were slain.
Banu Nadir plotted to assassinate the Prophet in Rabi‘ al-Awwal, 4 A.H.
Banu Ghatafan were close to attacking Madinah in Jumada al-Ula, 4 A.H.
The expedition of Hamrā’ al-Asad pursued the Quraysh after Uḥud.
The first to take up arms against the Muslims after Uḥud were Banu Asad bin Khuzaimah.
News reached Madinah that Talhah and Salamah, the sons of Khuwaylid, had gathered men.
Talhah and Salamah were calling them to war against the Messenger of Allah.
The Prophet dispatched a platoon of about one hundred and fifty men from the Helpers and the Emigrants under the command of Abū Salamah.
The Muslim force surprised Banu Asad in their own land.
The Muslim force scattered their gathering.
The Muslim force seized their livestock.
On the return, the old wound which Abū Salamah had sustained at Uḥud was aggravated.
Abū Salamah died soon after the expedition.
This expedition took place at the beginning of Muharram, 4 A.H.
On the fifth of Muharram, 4 A.H., news came that Khalid bin Sufyan al-Hudhali was mobilising his people and others to attack Muslim positions.
The Messenger of Allah sent ‘Abdullah bin Unays alone.
‘Abdullah bin Unays came upon Khalid bin Sufyan and struck him down.
‘Abdullah bin Unays remained away from Madinah for eighteen days.
‘Abdullah bin Unays returned with the head of Khalid bin Sufyan.
The Messenger of Allah gave ‘Abdullah bin Unays a staff.
‘Abdullah bin Unays kept this staff with him throughout his life.
Near his death, ‘Abdullah bin Unays instructed his family to shroud him with the staff.
In Safar, 4 A.H., a group from the tribes of ‘Udal and Qarah came to the Messenger of Allah in Madinah and asked that he send instructors to teach them.
The Prophet sent a group of his Companions as teachers.
Reports mention that they were six; other reports mention that they were ten.
Among those named as their leader are Murthid bin Abī Murthid al-Ghanawi; in other reports, ‘Asim bin Thabit.
They reached a place called ar-Raji‘, between Rabigh and Jeddah.
At ar-Raji‘, they were betrayed.
A hundred archers from Banu Lihyan surrounded them.
Banu Lihyan had been hired by Quraysh in retaliation for men of theirs who had been killed at Badr.
The Muslims withdrew to a height and took up a defensive position.
The enemy offered them security if they would come down and surrender.
‘Asim bin Thabit refused.
‘Asim bin Thabit fought until he and six others were killed.
Three remained alive: Khubayb bin ‘Adiy, Zayd bin ad-Dathinnah, and another Companion.
The Bedouins bound them after they descended under apparent safe-conduct.
The third Companion refused to accompany them in that state and was killed.
Khubayb bin ‘Adiy and Zayd bin ad-Dathinnah had both slain leaders of Quraysh at Badr.
Khubayb and Zayd were taken to Makkah and sold there.
Each was handed over to the family of the man he had killed.
Khubayb was held prisoner for some time.
Quraysh decided to execute Khubayb and took him out of the Haram to a place called Tan‘im.
Khubayb asked to pray two rak‘ahs before his execution, and they permitted him.
Khubayb prayed two rak‘ahs.
Quraysh killed Khubayb and crucified his body.
Guards were set to prevent his Companions from taking him down.
‘Amr bin Umayyah ad-Damri came by night, overpowered the guards, lowered Khubayb’s body, and buried him.
Safwan bin Umayyah purchased Zayd bin ad-Dathinnah.
Safwan took Zayd outside the Haram to kill him in vengeance for his father Umayyah.
Zayd bin ad-Dathinnah was killed outside the Haram.
‘Asim bin Thabit’s killers wanted to mutilate him and take part of his body.
They sent men to cut off a piece of him.`,
