    statementOfFactsText: `In Sha‘bān of the sixth year after Hijrah, news reached the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] that al-Ḥārith ibn Dirār, the chief of Banū al-Muṣṭaliq, had gathered his people and some allied Arabs with the intention of attacking Madinah.
The Prophet [pbuh] sent a man to verify the report.
He met al-Ḥārith, who did not conceal that he was preparing for war.
The enemy dispatched a scout toward the Muslim positions, who was captured by the Muslims and killed.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] ordered the Muslims to prepare for battle.
According to reports, he appointed Zayd bin Ḥārithah over Madinah in his absence.
Banners were given.
It is related that Abū Bakr carried the banner of the Muhājirūn.
It is related that Sa‘d bin ‘Ubādah carried the banner of the Anṣār.
The two forces met at a watering place known as al-Muraysi‘, in the territory of Banū al-Muṣṭaliq.
There was an exchange of arrows.
The Muslims advanced.
Some of the enemy were killed.
Many were taken prisoner.
A large amount of property came into Muslim hands.
Reports mention that only one Muslim fell, killed accidentally by a fellow Muslim from among the Helpers.
Among the captives was Juwayriyyah bint al-Ḥārith, the daughter of the chief of Banū al-Muṣṭaliq.
Her share of the spoils fell to Thābit bin Qays ibn Shamās or to one of his cousins.
She sought to ransom herself.
She approached the Messenger of Allah [pbuh].
He freed her and married her.
When the Muslims heard of this marriage, many of them set free the captives of Banū al-Muṣṭaliq.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] later married Zaynab bint Jaḥsh after her separation from Zayd bin Ḥārithah.
As the Muslims were returning from the campaign, a quarrel broke out between a man from the Muhājirūn and a man from the Anṣār over water or access to the spring.
Each of them called out to his group.
Voices were raised.
The words of the pre-Islamic period were mentioned.
‘Abdullāh bin Ubayy said: “They have crowded us in our own land.”
It is related that he said: “When we return to Madinah, the more honourable will surely expel the meaner from it.”
When news of his words reached the Messenger of Allah [pbuh], ‘Umar asked permission to kill him.
The Prophet [pbuh] refused.
He ordered that the caravan depart immediately, at an unusual time.
He led the army in continuous travel.
When they approached Madinah, ‘Abdullāh, the son of ‘Abdullāh bin Ubayy, stood at the entrance to the city with his sword and prevented his father from entering.
When the Prophet [pbuh] was informed, he allowed ‘Abdullāh bin Ubayy to enter the city and ordered his son to let him pass.
‘Ā’ishah bint Abī Bakr [r] accompanied the Prophet [pbuh] on that journey.
When the army was returning and had camped near Madinah, she went out at night to relieve herself.
On her way back, she realised that her necklace was missing.
She went back to search for it.
While she was away, the men responsible for carrying her litter lifted it and placed it on the camel, supposing she was inside it.
She was light in weight.
The women used to be carried in covered howdahs.
The army then moved, leaving her behind.
She did not find anyone when she returned.
She sat in the place where the army had camped.
Sleep overcame her.
Ṣafwān bin al-Mu‘aṭṭal as-Sulamī adh-Dhakwānī used to travel behind the army.
When he arrived at that place in the morning, he saw someone sleeping and recognised her.
He had seen her before the verse of the veil was revealed.
When he recognised her, he said: “Innā lillāhi wa innā ilayhi rāji‘ūn.”
She woke up and covered herself with her cloak.
He did not speak to her with any word other than that.
He brought his camel near, placed his foot so that she could mount, and then led the camel.
They reached the Muslims when they had halted during the day.
‘Abdullāh bin Ubayy and those who followed him spread words of slander against ‘Ā’ishah.
A number of Muslims repeated some of what they heard.
When they reached Madinah, ‘Ā’ishah [r] fell ill.
He would enter, give salām, ask how she was, and then leave.
After some days, she went out with Umm Mistah to relieve herself.
On their return, Umm Mistah stumbled and cursed her own son.
‘Ā’ishah [r] reproached her for cursing a man who had been present at Badr.
Umm Mistah replied that he had taken part in spreading the slander about her.
She asked the Messenger of Allah [pbuh] to allow her to go to her parents’ house.
She went to her parents.
She asked her mother about what was being said.
Her mother told her to take it lightly.
She wept that night and the following morning.
The Messenger of Allah [pbuh] gathered some of his Companions and consulted them.
He called for Barīrah, the servant of ‘Ā’ishah, and asked her concerning what she knew.
She testified only to good.
The Prophet [pbuh] stood on the pulpit and addressed the people.
The people of al-Aws and al-Khazraj spoke, and their voices were raised.
He calmed them.
He went to ‘Ā’ishah [r] at her parents’ house.
She asked her father to answer on her behalf; he said that he did not know what to say.
She asked her mother; she likewise said she did not know what to say.
She recited: “So patience is most fitting, and it is Allah Whose help is sought against what you describe.”
He recited the verses revealed in Sūrat an-Nūr regarding the incident.
It is related that Miṣṭaḥ bin Uthāthah was flogged eighty lashes for false accusation.
It is related that Ḥassān bin Thābit was flogged eighty lashes for false accusation.
It is related that Ḥamnah bint Jaḥsh was flogged eighty lashes for false accusation.
It is related that about a month after this, the Prophet [pbuh] said to ‘Umar bin al-Khaṭṭāb words to the effect that if he had ordered the man to be killed at the beginning many nobles would have defended him, but that today, if he were to command his killing, they would carry it out.`,
