    statementOfFactsText: `The Treaty of al-Ḥudaybiyah occurred in Dhū al-Qa‘dah, 6 AH.
In the sixth year after Hijrah, the Prophet set out toward Makkah at the head of around one thousand four hundred Muslims.
He was accompanied by his wife Umm Salamah.
The Muslims carried no weapons except sheathed swords.
Ibn Umm Maktūm was appointed to oversee Madinah in the Prophet’s absence.
At Dhū’l-Ḥulayfah, the sacrificial animals were garlanded.
At Dhū’l-Ḥulayfah, all the believers entered iḥrām.
A scout was sent ahead to gather intelligence.
The scout returned with news that Quraysh had mobilized a large force, including many of their slaves, to block the way.
The Muslims agreed that they would not fight anyone unless prevented from performing the pilgrimage.
Quraysh dispatched two hundred horsemen under Khālid bin al-Walīd to monitor the Muslims.
The Muslims performed the prayer of fear while under threat.
They changed their route, avoiding the main approach and taking a rugged, rocky path.
When they reached Thaniyat al-Marār, the Prophet’s camel knelt and refused to move.
The Muslims camped at the far side of al-Ḥudaybiyah, near a meager well.
Budayl bin Warqā’ al-Khuza‘ī and other leaders of Khuza‘ah, who were allies of the Prophet, came and asked about his purpose.
He said he had not come for war, but only to perform ‘Umrah in the Sacred Sanctuary.
Quraysh sent Mikraz bin Ḥafs, and he returned with the same reply.
Al-Ḥulays bin ‘Alqamah, leader of the Ḥums, came after Mikraz.
‘Urwah bin Mas‘ūd al-Thaqafī came to negotiate.
Al-Mughīrah bin Shu‘bah struck ‘Urwah’s hand with the flat of his sword when ‘Urwah reached out to touch the Prophet’s beard.
Some young men of Quraysh infiltrated the Muslim camp.
Muḥammad bin Maslamah, commander of the guards, captured them.
The Messenger of Allāh released them.
The Prophet asked ‘Umar bin al-Khaṭṭāb to go to the Qurayshite notables.
‘Umar explained that he had no strong clan protection in Makkah.
‘Umar suggested ‘Uthmān bin ‘Affān instead.
‘Uthmān conveyed to Abū Sufyān and the chiefs that the Muslims had come only to honor the House and worship, not to fight.
Quraysh refused to let the Muslims enter that year.
Quraysh offered ‘Uthmān the chance to circumambulate the Ka‘bah alone.
‘Uthmān refused to circumambulate the Ka‘bah while the Prophet was prevented.
A rumor spread in the Muslim camp that ‘Uthmān had been killed.
The Prophet called the believers to pledge under a tree that they would not flee.
This is the Bay‘at al-Riḍwān.
Abū Sinān al-Asadī and Salamah bin al-Akwa‘ were among the first to pledge.
The Prophet took the pledge with his right hand and then placed his left hand in his right on behalf of ‘Uthmān.
Suhayl bin ‘Amr came as Quraysh’s representative to agree to a peace treaty.
The Muslims would return to Madinah that year and come back the following year for ‘Umrah, staying no more than three days in Makkah.
They would bring no weapons except sheathed swords kept in their bags.
There would be no warfare between the two sides for ten years.
If anyone from Quraysh came to Muḥammad without the permission of his guardian, he would be returned to Quraysh.
If any of those with Muḥammad went back to Quraysh, they would not be returned.
Any tribe was free to ally with Muḥammad or with Quraysh.
When ‘Alī bin Abī Ṭālib wrote “Bismillāh al-Raḥmān al-Raḥīm,” Suhayl objected and asked him to write “Bi-smika Allāhumma.”
Suhayl objected to “Muḥammad, the Messenger of Allāh,” and asked to write “Muḥammad son of ‘Abdullāh.”
The Prophet erased the words “the Messenger of Allāh” and dictated “Muḥammad son of ‘Abdullāh.”
While the treaty was being finalized, Suhayl’s son Abū Jandal arrived, dragging his chains, having escaped from Makkah.
Suhayl insisted that the terms had already been agreed verbally and that Abū Jandal be returned.
Abū Jandal was taken back to Makkah in chains.
After the treaty was concluded, the Prophet ordered his Companions to slaughter their sacrificial animals and shave or shorten their hair.
Umm Salamah advised the Prophet to go out, slaughter his animal, and have his head shaved without speaking to them.
It was established that a camel suffices for seven men, and likewise a cow for seven, in sacrificial rites.
During this journey, Ka‘b bin ‘Ujrah, who was in iḥrām and suffering from a severe condition on his head, was permitted to shave his head with fidyah: fasting three days, feeding six needy people, or slaughtering one sheep.
Around this time, believing women emigrated to Madinah seeking refuge.
When their families demanded that they be returned under the treaty’s terms, the Prophet declined to return them.
‘Umar bin al-Khaṭṭāb divorced two such wives.
One of these women later married Mu‘āwiyah bin Abī Sufyān.
The other later married Ṣafwān bin Umayyah.`,
