    statementOfFactsText: `Quraysh withdrew from the battlefield.
Quraysh entered a peaceful settlement with the Muslims.
After their banishment from Madinah, the Jews regrouped in Khaybar.
Soon after the treaty was concluded, the Messenger of Allāh made a decisive campaign against the Jews in Khaybar a first priority.
Toward the end of the sixth year AH, upon returning from al-Hudaybiyah, the Messenger of Allāh resolved to send written invitations to the rulers beyond Arabia.
He had a silver seal made bearing the words “Muḥammad Rasūl Allāh,” arranged in three lines: “Muḥammad,” “Rasūl,” “Allāh.”
Envoys were dispatched in Muḥarram 7 AH.
The envoys were dispatched a few days before the expedition of Khaybar.
Negus (al-Najāshī) was king of Abyssinia.
Negus’s name was Ashama ibn al-Abjar.
The Prophet sent a letter to Negus.
The letter to Negus was delivered by ‘Amr ibn Umayyah ad-Damrī.
Ja‘far ibn Abī Ṭālib and other emigrants came to Negus.
The Messenger of Allāh had previously recommended that Negus treat them with generosity.
One wording of the letter to Negus states: “This letter is from Muḥammad, the Prophet, to Negus al-Ashama, the king of Abyssinia.”
Negus wrote in reply to the Messenger of Allāh.
Negus later sent Ja‘far ibn Abī Ṭālib and the remaining emigrants back at the request of the Messenger of Allāh.
The emigrants rejoined the Prophet at Khaybar.
Negus died in Rajab of the ninth year AH.
The Messenger of Allāh informed his Companions of Negus’s death on the same day.
The Messenger of Allāh led them in funeral prayer in absentia for Negus.
After Negus, another king ruled Abyssinia.
The Prophet sent a further letter inviting that successor to Islam.
It is not definitively known whether that successor embraced Islam.
One wording of Negus’s reply begins: “From Negus Ashama to Muḥammad, the Messenger of Allāh.”`,
