    statementOfFactsText: `The skirmish at Dhu Qarad occurred after the Treaty of al-Hudaybiyah and shortly before the expedition to Khaybar.
The skirmish at Dhu Qarad was against a party from Banū Fazārah.
Dhu Qarad is a watering place about a day’s journey from Madinah.
The Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] sent his hireling Rabah with the Prophet’s camels to a nearby pasture.
Salamah ibn al-Akwaʿ took the horse of Ṭalḥah ibn ʿUbaydillāh and went to the same grazing area at dawn.
At daybreak, a raiding party led by ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Fazārī attacked.
The raiding party drove off all the camels.
The raiding party killed the man who was tending the camels.
Salamah ordered Rabah to mount Ṭalḥah’s horse.
Salamah ordered Rabah to return to Madinah.
Salamah ordered Rabah to inform the Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] that the polytheists had taken his camels.
Salamah climbed a hillock.
Salamah turned his face toward Madinah.
Salamah gave the alarm cry, calling the Muslims to help.
Salamah set out alone on foot in pursuit of the raiders.
Salamah shot arrows at the raiders as he ran.
Salamah hamstrung their animals with arrows.
When a horseman turned toward him, Salamah took cover behind a tree, sat at its base, loosed an arrow, and hamstrung the man’s mount.
The raiders entered a narrow mountain pass.
Salamah climbed above the raiders and held them at bay by hurling stones.
Salamah forced the raiders to abandon what they had taken.
Salamah recovered all the camels.
As they fled, the raiders dropped many cloaks and lances.
Salamah placed a stone by each item the raiders discarded.
The Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] and his Companions could later identify the discarded items as enemy property left behind.
The raiders halted in a narrow valley.
The raiders sat down to eat.
Salamah climbed a tapering rock above the raiders.
Four of the raiders began to climb up toward Salamah.
When they were within hearing distance, Salamah identified himself as Salamah ibn al-Akwaʿ.
The raiders turned back.
Salamah saw horsemen of the Muslims approaching through the trees.
At their head was Akhram al-Asadī, followed by Abū Qatādah al-Anṣārī, and then al-Miqdād ibn al-Aswad.
Akhram and ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Fazārī met in combat.
Akhram hamstrung the enemy’s horse.
ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Fazārī struck Akhram with his lance.
ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Fazārī killed Akhram.
ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Fazārī mounted Akhram’s horse and tried to ride away.
Abū Qatādah overtook ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Fazārī.
Abū Qatādah engaged ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Fazārī.
Abū Qatādah killed ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Fazārī.
The remaining polytheists fled in different directions.
Before sunset, they reached a valley with a spring called Dhu Qarad.
Salamah continued to chase them on foot until they reached Dhu Qarad.
The raiders stopped at Dhu Qarad to drink.
Salamah reached them at Dhu Qarad.
Salamah drove them away from the water before they could drink.
Later, the Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] arrived with a group of his Companions at Dhu Qarad.
The Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] caught up with Salamah at Dhu Qarad.
Salamah requested permission to select a hundred men and pursue the raiders further.
The Prophet [pbuh] said that the raiders had reached the dwellings of Ghaṭafān.
The Prophet [pbuh] said that the raiders were being hosted in the dwellings of Ghaṭafān.
The Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] allotted Salamah a double share of the spoils: the share of a horseman and the share of a foot soldier.
The Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] combined both shares for Salamah.
They prepared to return to Madinah.
The Prophet [pbuh] seated Salamah behind himself on his she-camel al-ʿAdbāʾ for the journey back.
The Muslims recovered the Prophet’s camels.`,
