    statementOfFactsText: `Reports mention that news reached the Prophet [pbuh] that groups from Banū Muhārib and Banū Thaʿlabah of Ghatafān were gathering men to confront the Muslims.
The Prophet [pbuh] went out with a group of his Companions toward the Najd region.
Narrations differ about their number, some mentioning about four hundred and others about seven hundred.
He appointed a deputy over Madinah in his absence.
Among the names mentioned in the reports are Abū Dharr and ʿUthmān b. ʿAffān.
The Muslims advanced into the lands of Ghatafān until they reached an area known as Nakhlah in that direction.
They encountered some of the Bedouins at Nakhlah.
No major battle took place at Nakhlah.
Reconciliation was reached at Nakhlah.
During this expedition, the Prophet [pbuh] led his Companions in Ṣalāt al-Khawf.
Abū Mūsā al-Ashʿarī [r] relates that they were a small group sharing a single camel, taking turns riding it.
Abū Mūsā al-Ashʿarī [r] relates that their feet became badly wounded.
Abū Mūsā al-Ashʿarī [r] relates that their nails fell off.
Abū Mūsā al-Ashʿarī [r] relates that they wrapped their feet in strips of cloth.
The expedition was called Dhāt al-Riqāʿ, “the Expedition of Patches.”
Jābir b. ʿAbdillāh [r] relates that during one of the Prophet’s campaigns toward Najd they came to a leafy tree.
The Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] rested beneath the tree.
He hung his sword upon one of its branches.
A man from the enemy came and seized the sword.
The Prophet [pbuh] awoke to find the sword drawn in the man’s hand.
The matter ended without the man harming the Prophet [pbuh].
In some narrations, the sword fell and the Prophet [pbuh] took it.
Reports also mention that on this expedition, a woman from among the Arabs was taken captive.
Her husband approached the Muslim camp by night.
He found ʿAbbād b. Bishr [r] standing guard in prayer, with ʿAmmār b. Yāsir [r] resting nearby.
The attacker loosed an arrow that struck ʿAbbād.
ʿAbbād removed the arrow and continued praying.
He was struck a second time and then a third time.
He did not break his prayer until he had completed the sūrah he was reciting.
He awakened his companion.
The aggressor fled.
Reports mention that Ghālib b. ʿAbdullāh al-Laythī led a detachment during Ṣafar or Rabīʿ al-Awwal in the seventh year after Hijrah against a group from Banū al-Mulūḥ.
The group from Banū al-Mulūḥ was involved in hostile activity near the Ḥijāz routes.
The Muslims engaged them.
Some of their fighters were killed.
Livestock was taken as booty.
A sizeable force set out to pursue the Muslims.
Heavy rainfall and floodwaters hindered the pursuers.
The Muslims returned safely.
In the same year, the Prophet [pbuh] dispatched ʿUmar b. al-Khaṭṭāb [r] at the head of about thirty men toward Ṭurbah.
People from Hawāzin were gathering at Ṭurbah with hostile intent.
When ʿUmar and his men approached Ṭurbah, the enemy scattered and fled before any clash occurred.
The detachment returned without battle.
Around Shaʿbān of that year, about thirty men under Bashīr b. Saʿd al-Anṣārī [r] set out toward Banū Murrah near the lands of Fadak.
The Muslims surprised Banū Murrah.
Some of their warriors were killed.
The Muslims drove off camels and cattle as booty.
On their return, the enemy regrouped and ambushed them by night.
They were showered with arrows.
Most of the Muslims were killed.
Bashīr b. Saʿd was gravely wounded.
He reached the vicinity of Fadak.
He stayed among the Jews until his wounds healed.
He returned to the Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] and informed him of what had occurred.
Later in the same year, Ghālib b. ʿAbdullāh al-Laythī led another expedition with about one hundred and thirty men.
This expedition was against groups from Banū ʿAwāl and Banū ʿAbd b. Thaʿlabah.
The Muslims launched a surprise attack at dawn.
A number of men were killed.
Livestock and other spoils were seized.
During one of these raids, Usāmah b. Zayd [r] killed a man from the enemy after the man had pronounced the testimony of faith.
When the news reached the Prophet [pbuh], he said to Usāmah: “Did you split open his heart to know whether he was truthful or lying?”
Reports mention that the Prophet [pbuh] learned of Asīr (or Bashīr) b. Razām, a leader among the Jews of the Khaybar region.
Asīr b. Razām was seeking the assistance of Ghatafān to launch a new attack on the Muslims.
The Prophet [pbuh] sent ʿAbdullāh b. Rawāḥah [r] with a group of horsemen to bring Asīr to Madinah under safe-conduct.
ʿAbdullāh b. Rawāḥah and his men assured Asīr that if he came to the Prophet [pbuh] and accepted terms, he would be left in charge over his people in Khaybar.
Asīr agreed and set out with them, accompanied by a number of his followers.
Tension arose on the way, and each side feared treachery from the other.
The situation escalated into a sudden clash.
ʿAbdullāh b. Rawāḥah and his Companions killed Asīr and his men.
In Shawwāl of the seventh year after Hijrah, the Prophet [pbuh] sent Bashīr b. Saʿd al-Anṣārī with about three hundred warriors.
This expedition was toward the region between Yemen and Jabar.
A large number of polytheists were said to be gathering to raid the outskirts of Madinah and the caravan routes.
The Muslims traveled by night and concealed themselves by day.
When news of the Muslim force reached them, the polytheists fled.
The polytheists abandoned their animals and equipment.
The Muslims took considerable booty.
The Muslims brought the booty back to Madinah.
Among those captured were two men who later embraced Islām before the Prophet [pbuh].
Before the Compensatory ʿUmrah, reports mention a man named Jashm b. Muʿāwiyah who came to an area called Ghābah to rally Qays and others against the Muslims.
The Messenger of Allāh [pbuh] sent Abū Ḥadrad al-Aslamī [r] with two other men.
Abū Ḥadrad infiltrated their gathering.
He observed their numbers and preparation.
He struck their leader and scattered the group.
The enemy dispersed.
The Muslims captured livestock and other property.
The Muslims brought the property back to Madinah.`,
