    statementOfFactsText: `While the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ was still at al-Jiʿrānah with the spoils of Ḥunayn, a delegation from Hawāzin arrived as Muslims.
They were fourteen men led by Zuhayr ibn Ṣard.
Among them were men who were related to the Prophet ﷺ through fosterage.
They requested that he return to them some of their wealth and captives.
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ said to them, “When I perform the noon prayer, stand and say: ‘We intercede with the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ to exhort the believers, and we intercede with the believers to exhort the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ to release the captives of our people who have fallen to their lot.’”
When the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ had led them in the ẓuhr prayer, they stood and said what he had instructed them to say.
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ said, “As for what belongs to me and to the children of ʿAbd al-Muṭṭalib, you may consider it yours from now on.”
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ said, “I will also speak to my kinsmen so that they return their shares.”
The Emigrants (al-Muhājirūn) and the Helpers (al-Anṣār) said, “Whatever belongs to us is offered to the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ.”
Al-Aqraʿ ibn Ḥābis said, “We will not give up what belongs to me and to Banū Tamīm.”
ʿUyaynah ibn Ḥiṣn said, “As for me and Banū Fazārah, we say no.”
Al-ʿAbbās ibn Mirdās initially refused and said “No” on behalf of himself and Banū Sulaym.
The people of Banū Sulaym said, “Whatever spoils belong to us, we offer to the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ.”
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ said, “Therefore, whoever among you willingly gives back what he possesses of their captives, let him do so.”
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ said, “Whoever wishes to keep what he owns, let him do so, and he will be given as compensation six times as much from the next booty that Allāh grants us.”
The people said, “We will willingly return everything for the sake of the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ.”
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ said, “Go back, and your chiefs will return to inform us of your decisions.”
Their leaders came back to the Prophet ﷺ and informed him that the people were content to return the captives.
The women and children of Hawāzin were released and returned.
ʿUyaynah ibn Ḥiṣn initially refused to release an elderly woman who had fallen to his lot, but he later released her.
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ gave each freed captive a garment as a gift.
After completing the matter of the spoils and the captives at al-Jiʿrānah, the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ departed while in the raiment of iḥrām and proceeded to Makkah to perform ʿumrah.
He entered the Sacred Mosque, performed ṭawāf and saʿy, and completed the rites of the lesser pilgrimage.
When he had finished his ʿumrah, he returned to Madīnah.
He appointed ʿItāb ibn Usayd as governor over Makkah.
His arrival in Madīnah was during the last six nights of Dhū al-Qaʿdah in the eighth year after the Hijrah.
This episode is related in the major sīrah and ḥadīth sources, including Ibn Hishām (2/389–501), Ibn al-Qayyim in Zād al-Maʿād (2/160–201), al-Bukhārī in the chapters on the Conquest of Ḥunayn, Awtās, and Ṭāʾif, with commentary in Fatḥ al-Bārī (8/3–58), and in modern arrangement in Fiqh al-Sīrah.`,
