    statementOfFactsText: `The Muslim army returned from Tabūk to Madīnah.
On the way back, they were passing along a narrow mountain path.
At that time, the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ was riding with only ʿAmmār holding the rein of his she-camel.
Ḥudhayfah ibn al-Yamān was driving the she-camel from behind.
The rest of the people had already descended into the bottom of the valley.
Some hypocrites came up from behind with their faces covered, intending to startle the Prophet’s mount and cast him down.
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ instructed Ḥudhayfah to go and see who they were.
Ḥudhayfah went forward and struck the faces of their riding animals with a stick he had in his hand.
They turned back in haste and rejoined their people.
Ḥudhayfah later informed the Prophet ﷺ of who they were and of their intention.
From that time, Ḥudhayfah was known among the Companions as the keeper of the Prophet’s secret regarding the names of certain hypocrites.
Uḥud is a mountain.
When the people of Madīnah learned of the army’s return, they went out to meet them.
Men, women, youths, and children came forth to welcome the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ and his Companions.
The march to Tabūk began in the month of Rajab.
The return to Madīnah was in Ramaḍān.
The entire expedition lasted around fifty days.
About twenty days were spent encamped at Tabūk.
The remainder of the time was spent on the journey to and from the frontier.
The Tabūk expedition was the last campaign led in person by the Prophet ﷺ.
When the Messenger of Allāh ﷺ returned to Madīnah, he entered the mosque and prayed two rakʿahs.
Then he sat so that people could come to him.
The hypocrites came and began to present their excuses and swear oaths.
The three sincere believers who did not present false excuses were Kaʿb ibn Mālik, Murārah ibn ar-Rabīʿ, and Hilāl ibn Umayyah.
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ ordered the Muslims not to speak to Kaʿb ibn Mālik, Murārah ibn ar-Rabīʿ, and Hilāl ibn Umayyah.
After about forty days, they were instructed to separate from their wives.
After fifty days had passed, Qur’ān 9:118 was revealed concerning them.
He commanded the Muslims to demolish the mosque which the hypocrites had built—Masjid ad-Dirār.
Many verses from Sūrat at-Tawbah (Barā’ah) were revealed in connection with the expedition to Tabūk.
Some of those verses came down before the march.
Other verses were revealed during the journey and at the time of the campaign.
Further verses were revealed after the return to Madīnah.
One of the important events of that year was the case of mutual imprecation (liʿān) between ʿUwaymir al-ʿAjlānī and his wife.
They both appeared before the Prophet ﷺ and performed the prescribed oaths.
After the completion of the oaths, they were separated and their marriage was dissolved.
Another event was the stoning of a woman from the tribe of Ghamīd who came to the Prophet ﷺ confessing adultery.
He ordered that the prescribed punishment be delayed until she had given birth to her child.
He ordered that it be delayed until she had weaned the child.
When that was completed, the legal punishment was carried out upon her.
In that year also died an-Najāshī, Ashamah, the king of Abyssinia.
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ informed his Companions of his death on the day it occurred.
He led them in the funeral prayer in absentia.
The Prophet’s daughter Umm Kulthūm, the wife of ʿUthmān ibn ʿAffān, died that year.
After the return from Tabūk, ʿAbdullāh ibn Ubayy ibn Salūl fell ill and died.
The Messenger of Allāh ﷺ went to him while he was sick.
Upon his death his son requested that the Prophet ﷺ give him his shirt to be used as a shroud.
The Prophet ﷺ gave it to him.
The Prophet ﷺ stood to pray over ʿAbdullāh ibn Ubayy ibn Salūl.
ʿUmar ibn al-Khaṭṭāb tried to dissuade the Prophet ﷺ from praying over him.
Verses were revealed later forbidding the Prophet ﷺ from praying over those who were clearly known for hypocrisy and died in a state of disbelief.
This account follows the reports in Ibn Hishām (as-Sīrah an-Nabawiyyah 2/422–600).
This account follows the reports in Ibn Saʿd (aṭ-Ṭabaqāt 2/175–190).
This account follows the reports in at-Ṭabarī (Tārīkh al-Umam wa’l-Mulūk events of year 9 A.H.).
This account follows the reports in Ibn Kathīr (al-Bidāyah wa’n-Nihāyah 5/42–80).
This account follows the reports in Ibn al-Qayyim (Zād al-Maʿād 3/39–90).
This account follows the authentic narrations in Ṣaḥīḥ al-Bukhārī and Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim.`,
